  <!-- Section 1: What Is -->
  <section class="section" id="what-is">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <span class="section-label">Background</span>
      <h2 class="section-title text-balance">What Exactly Is the China Green Card?</h2>
      <p>The "China green card" is the popular name for the <strong>Permanent Residence Permit for Aliens</strong> — officially known since 2020 as the <strong>"Five-Star Card" (五星卡)</strong>. It is the highest level of residency China grants to foreigners short of citizenship.</p>
      <p>Unlike a work visa or a temporary residence permit, the China green card does not expire annually. Adults receive a card valid for <strong>10 years</strong>; minors receive one valid for <strong>5 years</strong>. Once granted, it functions as your primary ID in China — eliminating the need for annual visa renewal and granting you most of the same everyday rights as Chinese citizens.</p>

      <div class="pullquote">
        "Getting a permanent residence permit is essentially acquiring a decade-long, multiple-entry right to live, work, and build your life in China — without touching an immigration counter every 12 months."
      </div>

      <p>The card is issued by the provincial <strong>Public Security Bureau (PSB)</strong> Exit-Entry Administration. It is different from:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>A <strong>Z visa</strong> (work visa) — temporary and employer-tied</li>
        <li>A <strong>temporary residence permit (居留许可)</strong> — renewed annually, linked to job or family status</li>
        <li>A <strong>Chinese citizenship</strong> — China does not offer naturalisation to most foreigners</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="info-box" role="note">
        <span class="info-box-icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
            <circle cx="10" cy="10" r="9" stroke="#1d4ed8" stroke-width="1.5"></circle>
            <path d="M10 9v5M10 7h.01" stroke="#1d4ed8" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
          </svg>
        </span>
        <span class="info-box-text"><strong>Note on terminology:</strong> "China residence permit for foreigners," "China permanent residence card," and "china green card" all refer to the same document in everyday usage. We use "green card" throughout this guide for clarity.</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section 2: Who Qualifies -->
  <section class="section section--cream" id="who-qualifies">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="section-label">Eligibility</span>
      <h2 class="section-title text-balance">Who Qualifies for a China Green Card in 2026?</h2>
      <p class="section-lead">China's permanent residence rules are strict and specific. There are four main pathways, each with concrete income, tenure, and background requirements. Every applicant must also have clean criminal records and be in good health.</p>

      <div class="pathway-grid">
        <article class="pathway-card">
          <div class="pathway-icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#0f1f3d" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <rect x="2" y="7" width="20" height="14" rx="2"></rect><path d="M16 7V5a2 2 0 0 0-2-2h-4a2 2 0 0 0-2 2v2"></path>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h4>A. High-Earning Professionals</h4>
          <p style="font-size:.85rem; margin-bottom:10px;">For salaried employees in China who meet strict income and tax thresholds.</p>
          <ul style="font-size:.85rem;">
            <li>Valid work (Z) visa and local employment</li>
            <li>Earn at least <strong>886,104 RMB/year</strong> (Shanghai, 2026)</li>
            <li>Pay at least <strong>177,221 RMB/year</strong> in personal income tax</li>
            <li>4 consecutive years in China, ≥6 months/year physically present</li>
            <li>No criminal record in China or abroad</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="pathway-card">
          <div class="pathway-icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#0f1f3d" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M12 2L2 7l10 5 10-5-10-5z"></path><path d="M2 17l10 5 10-5"></path><path d="M2 12l10 5 10-5"></path>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h4>B. Talent Track (Academics &amp; Specialists)</h4>
          <p style="font-size:.85rem; margin-bottom:10px;">China waives income benchmarks for recognized high-level talent and urgently needed specialists.</p>
          <ul style="font-size:.85rem;">
            <li>PhD holders (especially from Chinese institutions or key fields)</li>
            <li>Professors, researchers in AI, biotech, renewable energy</li>
            <li>Senior professionals at government-affiliated organisations</li>
            <li>Members of national "talent introduction" programmes</li>
            <li>Associate senior professional titles or above</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="pathway-card">
          <div class="pathway-icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#0f1f3d" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <path d="M17 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-4-4H5a4 4 0 0 0-4 4v2"></path><circle cx="9" cy="7" r="4"></circle><path d="M23 21v-2a4 4 0 0 0-3-3.87"></path><path d="M16 3.13a4 4 0 0 1 0 7.75"></path>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h4>C. Spouses &amp; Family of Chinese Citizens</h4>
          <p style="font-size:.85rem; margin-bottom:10px;">Marriage to a Chinese national is one of the most common green card routes for Western expats.</p>
          <ul style="font-size:.85rem;">
            <li>Married to a Chinese citizen or green card holder for <strong>5+ years</strong></li>
            <li>Physically in China for 5 years, ≥9 months/year</li>
            <li><strong>200,000 RMB</strong> in a Chinese bank account (Shanghai; varies by city)</li>
            <li>Clean criminal record</li>
            <li>Children under 18 and elderly dependents may also apply</li>
          </ul>
        </article>

        <article class="pathway-card">
          <div class="pathway-icon" aria-hidden="true">
            <svg width="22" height="22" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="#0f1f3d" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
              <line x1="12" y1="1" x2="12" y2="23"></line><path d="M17 5H9.5a3.5 3.5 0 1 0 0 7h5a3.5 3.5 0 1 1 0 7H6"></path>
            </svg>
          </div>
          <h4>D. Investors &amp; Business Owners</h4>
          <p style="font-size:.85rem; margin-bottom:10px;">Entrepreneurs who have made substantial, sustained investments in Chinese businesses.</p>
          <ul style="font-size:.85rem;">
            <li>Minimum investment: <strong>500,000 USD – 2 million USD</strong> depending on region &amp; sector</li>
            <li>Held company shares for <strong>3+ years</strong></li>
            <li>Demonstrable tax payments and lawful employment of staff</li>
            <li>Business operating and compliant with Chinese law</li>
          </ul>
        </article>
      </div>

      <div class="alert" role="note">
        <span class="alert-icon" aria-hidden="true">
          <svg width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none">
            <path d="M10 1L1 17h18L10 1z" stroke="#c2410c" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linejoin="round"></path>
            <path d="M10 8v4M10 14h.01" stroke="#c2410c" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></path>
          </svg>
        </span>
        <span class="alert-text"><strong>2026 update:</strong> Physical presence requirements are now more strictly enforced. Applicants must show stamped passport evidence of being in China for the required period — gaps due to travel are counted. Salary thresholds also increase annually in major cities like Shanghai and Beijing.</span>
      </div>

      <div class="cta-box">
        <div class="cta-box-text">
          <h3>Not sure which pathway fits your situation?</h3>
