  <!-- Section 9: Should You Apply -->
  <section class="section section--cream" id="decision">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <span class="section-label">Decision Framework</span>
      <h2 class="section-title text-balance">Should You Apply for a China Green Card — or Keep Renewing?</h2>
      <p>The answer depends on your long-term plans, your current pathway eligibility, and how much the annual renewal hassle costs you in time and disruption. Here is a practical framework.</p>

      <div class="decision-cols" style="margin: 32px 0;">
        <div class="decision-card yes">
          <h3>Apply for the Green Card If...</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You plan to stay in China for 5+ more years</li>
            <li>You are married to a Chinese national and meet the 5-year threshold</li>
            <li>Annual renewal is costing you time, money, and work disruption</li>
            <li>You want to buy property in China without restrictions</li>
            <li>You want to change jobs freely without immigration paperwork</li>
            <li>You value the ID card functionality for everyday convenience</li>
            <li>Your income meets the professional track thresholds</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="decision-card no">
          <h3>Consider Waiting If...</h3>
          <ul>
            <li>You are under 2 years into your China residence — you won't yet qualify</li>
            <li>Your plans are uncertain and you may leave within 2–3 years</li>
            <li>Your income is below the thresholds and you don't qualify yet</li>
            <li>You are in the middle of a job change that affects your eligibility</li>
            <li>Your marriage is under 5 years old (spouse track)</li>
            <li>You have not met the physical presence days requirement yet</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="pullquote">
        "For expats in China more than four years, the annual work permit renewal is often a bigger productivity drain than people admit. One approval process per decade versus one per year is not a marginal gain — it is a fundamental change in how you relate to the country."
