  <!-- Section 10: FAQ -->
  <section class="section" id="faq">
    <div class="container--narrow">
      <span class="section-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="section-title text-balance">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <p style="margin-bottom: 36px;">Direct answers to the questions we hear most from American, British, and Australian expats considering the Chinese green card application.</p>

      <ul class="faq-list" role="list">
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            How do I get permanent residency in China as an American?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Americans qualify under the same rules as all other foreigners. The most accessible routes are the professional track (requiring 4 consecutive years in China with a high salary and tax payments) and the spouse track (married to a Chinese citizen for 5+ years with 5 years of physical residence). Americans need an apostilled FBI background check and a health check from an approved clinic. Working with a consultancy based in China is recommended for Americans, as the PSB process is handled entirely in Mandarin and local knowledge is critical.</div>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            What are the requirements for a China green card in 2026?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">In 2026, the main china green card requirements are: (1) Professional track — 4 years of employment in China earning at least 886,104 RMB/year (Shanghai) with at least 177,221 RMB/year in personal income tax; (2) Spouse track — 5 years of marriage to a Chinese citizen, 5 years of physical residence in China at 9+ months/year, and 200,000 RMB in a Chinese bank account; (3) Investor track — 500,000–2,000,000 USD invested for 3+ years. All applicants must have no criminal record and pass a health check. Salary and tax thresholds increase annually.</div>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            Is it worth getting a Chinese green card or should I just renew my work visa?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">If you plan to stay in China for 5 or more additional years and meet the eligibility criteria, the green card is almost always worth it. The main gains are: no annual permit renewal (saving significant time and money), freedom to change employers without immigration paperwork, ability to buy property under citizen rules, and everyday ID card functionality. The main cost is the application effort and 4–12 months of processing time. For shorter stays or uncertain plans, continuing on a work permit is reasonable. Our consultants can walk through your specific situation in a free call.</div>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            Can I get a China green card through marriage to a Chinese citizen?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Yes — china permanent residence through marriage is one of the most common routes for Western expats. To qualify you must: (1) have been married to a Chinese citizen for at least 5 years; (2) have physically lived in China for 5 consecutive years with at least 9 months per year; (3) maintain at least 200,000 RMB in a Chinese bank account (amount varies by city); and (4) have a clean criminal record and pass a health check. Processing times for the spousal route are the longest — typically 9–12 months in 2026. If your foreign marriage certificate was issued abroad, it must be apostilled and freshly notarized (within 6 months of application).</div>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            What is the cost involved in applying for a China green card in 2026?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">Government fees total approximately 1,800 RMB (1,500 RMB application + 300 RMB card issuance). Additional costs include: criminal background check and apostille (varies by country — USD 18–80 plus postage for Americans), notarization of foreign documents (200–800 RMB per document), certified translation services (300–600 RMB per document), and health check (typically 500–900 RMB). Total out-of-pocket costs for documents and government fees typically run between 5,000–15,000 RMB depending on your situation and city. Consultancy fees, if you use professional help, are separate and vary by provider.</div>
          </div>
        </li>
        <li class="faq-item">
          <button class="faq-question" aria-expanded="false" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
            How hard is it to get a Chinese green card?
            <svg class="faq-icon" width="20" height="20" viewBox="0 0 20 20" fill="none" aria-hidden="true"><line x1="10" y1="4" x2="10" y2="16" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line><line x1="4" y1="10" x2="16" y2="10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.8" stroke-linecap="round"></line></svg>
          </button>
          <div class="faq-answer">
            <div class="faq-answer-inner">China's permanent residency is considered one of the harder to obtain in Asia — primarily because the eligibility thresholds are high and strictly enforced. Fewer than 20,000 foreign nationals hold the card at any given time, out of millions of long-term residents. The process is not difficult if you genuinely meet the criteria; it is difficult to qualify in the first place. The biggest rejection causes are: insufficient physical presence evidence, improperly notarized foreign documents, income or tax records that don't meet the threshold, and applying under the wrong pathway. A well-prepared application from an eligible applicant has a high success rate.</div>
          </div>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

